text: Anybody have experience dealing with borderline personality disorder?
yes and no
whats up?
Actually, yes. A close friend used to struggle with extreme dissociation
my niece's grandmother on the other side -- pretty sure she has it
My mom
but if you're talking about dealing about it with yourself, then no
Well, undiagnosed, but . . .
Ditto what Patrick said
I just kicked my girlfriend out last week and we had a crazy relationship. While we were together how she acted just didn't add up.
I'm going to guess her perception of situations didn't match the reality?
I'm shocked that after a week I still miss her, love her even. But as I read back through our conversations I can't dispute that things were nuts and not healthy.
and everything was a do or die "do must love me" situation
Yeah sometimes <@U4V5EHQ2G>
Yeah <@U3RJ9VDRT>
it's always a test to see if you actually love them, and if you fail the test it blows up, and it's almost impossible to pass the test
I'm sorry to hear that, Chris :disappointed:
She got mad, I mean EXTREMELY mad over benign things. Like me spending time with my son. She would get mad and stop talking to me for days because "I would rather spend time with him."
yeah, you're better off without her right now Chris, it isn't healthy for your son to be around that kind of behavior if she isn't willing to work on it too

Thanks everyone. That's what lead me to kicking her out <@U3RJ9VDRT>. If she would get help it would be different, but everytime I offered to set up an appointment with my counselor and therapist she wouldn't agree to go.
yeah, my niece is SUPER jaded about her grandma because of that behavior
9 year olds shouldn't be jaded
That's sad. Nobody should have to go through that, especially at that age.
It's a really difficult thing to get people to get help with, too, because often BPD prevents them from seeing they have a problem in the first place.

I was just curious if any of what I'm describing seemed to fit what anyone else experienced. My counselor read our messages and is familiar with the stories and told me that she can't say for certain, but feels she likely suffers from BPD.
it's pretty in line with what I've experienced so far
@dana so true. Everytime I would bring it up I was the one with the problem. She's perfectly fine aside from my behavior, which she found largely intolerable.
also, I know it hurts real bad Chris, but love can't fix everything, and you need to do whats best for your son and you
Yeah <@U3RJ9VDRT>, it's true. It sucks, but it's true.
I know I made the right decision, but I can't help but wonder what her life will be like now without me. I think I got pretty enmeshed with her emotional and mental baggage.
yuuuuup
It's positive that you're seeing a therapist, if nothing else
fo' shizzle

Oh yeah I'll keep doing that regardless. I am my own colorful bowl of fruit loops in need of help. I'm not a victim or removed from guilt. I have my own personality issues that I have to stay on top of to remain productive and healthy.
That's likely what kept me in the picture for so long. Like somehow the issues I get help for lent credibility to her outlandish accusations.

It's important to help people you love and stick with them through hard times, but it's equally important to know when you can't help them and in trying you're just doing yourself and your life damage.
Agreed. I know the feeling of trying to make yourself responsible for someone else's happiness. It doesn't end well
Great point @dana
Yeah it seems so
Your level of self-awareness sounds positive as well
I'm glad you're approaching the situation with such a level-head, even though it hits so close to home
I've been doing mindfulness and cognitive behavioral therapy for over a year now.
Oh, fantastic
Thanks @atlas. I practice both because I was diagnosed with purely obsessional ocd and depression around that time. Been doing both since to help keep me grounded and keep from ruminating.
Understood
I appreciate your trust in openly discussing these topics
How is obsessional OCD different?
My tics are purely emotional/mental
They don't manifest physically in any way. Mine are mostly mental. I tend to ruminate obsessively and get lost in thought.
Do stereotypical behaviors break the cycle like they do with other forms of OCD?

No the way we have to combat Pure O is counter intuitive. If I'm ruminating I have to focus on exploring the w's that relate to the topic in question rather than what I normally want to do, which is tell myself to stop and that I'm crazy.
Sounds really inconvenient
The idea is that when you try to make your brain stop as an ocd sufferer, it compulsively trues to continue. Providing context and logic is a way to break that cyclem
But doesn't fix bad typing unfortunately. Yeah it sucks but I deal with it. Everyone has their battles.
Thanks for the insight <!channel>. I feel better now. This helped me more than you know.
Always happy to talk
I missed this conversation, but having dealt with clients with BPD, I agree with the channel.
